<br>
non styled hit - 391<br>
(fatigue \ to hit bonus \ defense)<br>
<br>
1 didn't test<br>
2 crushing blow (parry) (low\med\none) - 641<br>
3 placate (detaunt) (med\none\med bonus) - 391<br>
4 slam (followup 2) (med\med\none) - 641<br>
5 ruiner (anytime) (med\low\none) - 513<br>
6 frost hammer (side) (med\med\none) - 590<br>
7 provoke (taunt) (low\med\med penalty) - 557<br>
8 demolish (followup 5) (high\low\none) - 581<br>
9 revenge (block) (low\med\low penalty) - 641<br>
10 crumble (followup 5) (med\med\none) - 612<br>
11 conquer (back) (low\none\high penalty) - 641<br>
12 thor's answer (followup 9) (med\med\none) - 641<br>
13 lambast (parry) (low\med\low bonus) - 641<br>
14 sledgehammer (followup 11) (med\high\none) - 661<br>
15 dont have the level 50 style<br>
<br>
so what does this really tell us? <br>
<br>
first off there's a super 2 style combo off a parry that you get at 4 and 8 spec.  does as my damage as any other style other than sledgehammer, both are medium fatigue medium hit bonus.  if you've got a lot of parry this combo is awesome.  only drawback being short duration stun on crushing blow which would prevent healer stuns or shield stuns or thor's answer stuns, of course 2 of those are irrelevant if you use 2 hand weapon which nearly all skalds do.<br>
<br>
the entire ruiner chain situation is pretty gimpy.  ruiner is worst damage style of them all with the sole exception of the detaunt and has a low to hit bonus.  the first followup demolish has a low to hit bonus and a high end requirement for only ok damage, although it does have a short duration stun component making it good in rare situations.  such as against stealthers with fast attack weapons.  against slow attack weapons the stun wears off and has no effect, generally your target takes that time to use his first aid lol.  the other followup option is crumble, it's a decent style but i dont think it makes up for how bad ruiner is.  one extra note on the short duration stuns, these piss off berserkers pretty quick cuz they have a good stun style off an evade (which they do a lot of) so if you're playing with a berserker who isn't a nitwit who only uses the 34 spec anytime style you'll get an earfull pretty fast.<br>
<br>
frost hammer - this seems like a good style in zerg vs zerg but it takes some effort.  best used against mezd casters or against tanks who are tanking one of your tanks.  problem is that it takes some positioning which can be easily screwed up if you're fighting targets that are likely to move.  why is this not worse than conquer in every way you ask?  conquer has issues, frost hammer has medium to hit bonus and no penalties.  really depends on you but this is a decent style which shouldn't be ignored.<br>
<br>
provoke.  this is a decent style if you're not concerned about getting hit, as in you're fighting a caster only.  it doesn't do great damage, but it uses hardly any endurance to make up for it.  medium penalty on defense though so you're not going to parry or evade hardly ever.<br>
<br>
revenge - good style with long stun followup, but off a block.  would be nice if it was anyone blocks, but it's not you have to yourself.  which means this style is useless for skalds.<br>
<br>
conquer - if you're ambushing someone solo then this is great.  not because of conquer, because it sucks.  but because of it's followup.  conquer is a back positional, you'd think it would be high chance to hit since they can't see you coming right?  lol.  nope.  NO chance to hit, and a HIGH PENALTY to defense.  makes completely no sense, whoever created this style was a complete moron.  however that's the way it is.  you miss on conquer a LOT, which really sucks cuz then you're screwed and cant get off sledgehammer.  also, conquer does only ok not great damage.  if it does land though, there's really not much way to hit someone harder than with sledgehammer.<br>
<br>
and last, lambast.  parry reactionary.  it's good - low fatigue, medium chance to hit, low bonus to defense so you're more likely to parry again next round.  however it really isn't significantly better than crushing blow, which takes 35 less levels of hammer spec.  reason being is that there's no followup to lambast, so if you dont parry again you're stuck using an anytime style which is likely to be provoke.  which has a defense penalty hence making you less likely to parry again so you can use lambast.  kinda sucks that way.  if you have enough parry to actually have a parry reactionary on your styles bar you are better off with crushing blow.  other than if you are concerned with the low duration stun that comes with it.<br>
<br>
ok, there u go.<br>
